DADOS-GERAIS.NOME-EM-CITACOES-BIBLIOGRAFICAS: DIAS, H.J.;Dias, Herbert J.;Jnior, Herbert;DIAS, H. J.;DIAS, HERBERT JÚNIOR;DIAS, HERBERT;DIAS, HERBERT JUNIOR;HERBERT J;Herbert Júnior Dias

RESUMO-CV.TEXTO-RESUMO-CV-RH: Possui bacharelado em Química pela Universidade de Franca (2010), e Mestrado em Ciências pela mesma universidade (2013), onde desenvolveu projeto na área de produtos naturais, com ênfase na aplicação de espectrometria de massas para a determinação de padrões de fragmentação para fins de elucidação estrutural; e análise de óleos essenciais empregando técnicas hifenadas e suas respectivas atividades biológicas. Concluiu a sua formação de docente (Licenciatura) na mesma universidade (2015). Concluiu seu doutorado no Programa de Pós-graduação em Química na FFCLRP-USP (2018), onde desenvolveu projeto que envolveu síntese de análogos de produtos naturais e estudos de fragmentação empregando espectrometria de massas sequencial. Atualmente é professor no Instituto Federal de Educação, Ciência e Tecnologia Goiano - Campus Urutaí, membro do Núcleo de Química e do Programa de Pós-Graduação em Recursos Naturais do Cerrado (PPG-CRENAC). Desenvolve projetos na área de Química Orgânica, Química Analítica, Química dos Produtos Naturais, e Educação em Ciências.
RESUMO-CV.TEXTO-RESUMO-CV-RH-EN: Herbert J. Dias graduated in Chemistry at University of Franca (2010) and obtained his Master's degree in Sciences at the same university (2013). He developed research in natural products issues, mainly in applications of mass spectrometry in fragmentation studies for dereplication of compounds in crude mixtures, as well as analysis of essential oils employing hyphenated techniques and their biological activities. He concluded his Ph.D. student at Programa de Pós-Graduação em Química at DQ-FFCLRP-USP (2018), were developed a project involving synthesis and fragmentation studies of benzofuran compounds using ESI-MS/MS. Now he is a professor at the Instituto Federal de Educação, Ciência e Tecnologia Goiano - Campus Urutaí, member of Chemistry Nucleus and of the Pos-Graduating Program in Cerrado's Natural Resources. Develops projects in the areas of Organic Chemistry, Analytical Chemistry, Chemistry of Natural Products, and Science Education.

DADOS-BASICOS-DO-TRABALHO.TITULO-DO-TRABALHO-INGLES: Fragmentation of cholesterol and oxysterols by atmospheric pressure chemical ionization tandem mass spectrometry (APCI-MS/MS): a preliminary study

DETALHAMENTO-DO-TRABALHO.NOME-DO-EVENTO: Terceiro Congresso Brasileiro de Espectrometria de Massas
DETALHAMENTO-DO-TRABALHO.TITULO-DOS-ANAIS-OU-PROCEEDINGS: Fragmentation of cholesterol and oxysterols by atmospheric pressure chemical ionization tandem mass spectrometry (APCI-MS/MS): a preliminary study

INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS.DESCRICAO-INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS-INGLES: Cholesterol is susceptible to oxidation in presence of light, oxygen and high storage temperature.1 The cholesterol oxidation products (or ?oxysterols?) can be found in many processed dairy, meat and egg products. They have been reported to have atherogenic, cytotoxic, mutagenic and carcinogenic effects in both in vivo and in vitro studies.2 Liquid chromatography mass spectrometry (LC-MS and LC-MS/MS) has emerged as a very useful analytical technique for the analysis of cholesterol and oxysterols in foodstuffs, as an alternative to gas chromatography mass spectrometry (GC-MS).2 The aim of this study is to investigate the fragmentation of cholesterol and eight oxysterols using atmospheric pressure chemical ionization mass spectrometry (APCI-MS), aiming to achieve structure-fragmentation relationships to be used in the structural elucidation of oxysterols by LC-MS/MS. Mass spectral analyses were undertaken in an ion trap mass spectrometer fitted with a APCI source. All of the compounds were analyzed using the same experimental conditions. Proton affinities were obtained using computational calculations at B3LYP/6-31G(2df,p)//HF/6-31G(d) level. These values demonstrated that cholesterol is protonated at the oxygen hydroxyl, thus leading to the water elimination. Further fragmentation of [M+H-H2O]+ ion involves typical pericyclic reactions and 1,4-hydrogen rearrangements. The investigation of the fragmentation patterns of the selected oxysterols are in progress.
